  "prompt": "What is continuity versus discontinuity in developmental psychology?",
  "response": "In developmental psychology, the continuity versus discontinuity debate focuses on how individuals develop and change over time. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\nContinuity Perspective:\n1. Gradual, smooth progression of development\n2. Changes occur incrementally and continuously\n3. Skills and abilities develop gradually through small, consistent improvements\n4. Similar underlying processes throughout life stages\n5. Emphasizes cumulative learning and gradual skill acquisition\n\nDiscontinuity Perspective:\n1. Development occurs in distinct, qualitative stages\n2. Abrupt, significant shifts in cognitive, social, or emotional functioning\n3. Each stage represents a fundamental restructuring of understanding\n4. Different stages have unique characteristics and mechanisms\n5. Dramatic transformations in thinking and behavior\n\nKey Theorists:\n- Continuity: Albert Bandura, Information Processing theorists\n- Discontinuity: Jean Piaget (cognitive stages), Erik Erikson (psychosocial stages)\n\nExamples:\n- Continuity: Gradual language skill improvement\n- Discontinuity: Piaget's cognitive developmental stages (sensorimotor, preoperational, concrete operational, formal operational)\n\nModern perspectives often integrate both views, recognizing that development can involve both gradual changes and significant qualitative shifts.",
